>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Direct billing means the insurance company pays the hospital directly—you don't front thousands of dollars and wait for reimbursement. For any serious medical care, this matters enormously.
  </p>

  <p>
    After analyzing direct billing networks across major international insurers, here are our recommendations:
  </p>

  <h3>Largest Global Network: Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> Over 1.5 million healthcare providers in their network. Direct billing available at major hospitals in virtually every expat destination. Excellent app for finding providers and initiating claims.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Premium pricing. Network size doesn't guarantee every hospital—always verify before treatment.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Expats who want the most extensive direct billing network globally.
  </p>

  <h3>Premium Hospital Access: BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> 2,000+ directly-billed hospitals focused on quality over quantity. Relationships with top-tier facilities worldwide. If you want the best hospitals with seamless billing, BUPA delivers.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Most expensive option. Network smaller than Cigna by numbers, but quality-focused.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Those who prioritize access to the best hospitals over network size.
  </p>

  <h3>Best European Network: Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> Strong direct billing throughout Europe. German efficiency in network management. Good app for finding network providers.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Less comprehensive outside Europe. Global network smaller than Cigna/BUPA.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Europe-based expats who want seamless direct billing in European hospitals.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Direct Billing Coverage"
    description="Compare insurers with strong direct billing networks in your destination."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="why-direct-billing">Why Direct Billing Matters</h2>
  <p>
    The difference between direct billing and reimbursement is cash flow—and sometimes treatment access:
  </p>

  <h3>The Cash Flow Problem</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Without direct billing:</strong> You pay $15,000 for surgery. Wait 2-6 weeks for reimbursement. Hope your credit card has room.</li>
    <li><strong>With direct billing:</strong> Insurance pays the hospital. You pay your deductible/copay. Walk out without massive bills.</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency scenarios:</strong> In some countries, hospitals won't start treatment without payment guarantee. Direct billing solves this.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>How Direct Billing Works</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Find network provider:</strong> Use your insurer's app or website to find a hospital with direct billing.</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-authorization:</strong> For planned procedures, get approval before treatment. Emergency care usually doesn't require pre-auth.</li>
    <li><strong>Present your card:</strong> Show your insurance card at the hospital. They verify coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Receive treatment:</strong> Hospital bills insurance directly. You pay deductible/copay if applicable.</li>
    <li><strong>Claims processed:</strong> Insurance settles with hospital. You don't handle paperwork.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>When Direct Billing Isn't Available</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Out-of-network providers:</strong> You pay, then claim reimbursement.</li>
    <li><strong>Small clinics:</strong> Often cash-only; you pay and claim.</li>
    <li><strong>Pharmacies:</strong> Usually pay-and-claim, though some networks include pharmacies.</li>
    <li><strong>Remote locations:</strong> Less likely to have network providers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Pre-Authorization</h3>
  <p>
    Most planned treatments require pre-authorization for direct billing:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Emergency:</strong> No pre-auth needed—get treated, sort paperwork later.</li>
    <li><strong>Planned inpatient:</strong> Request authorization 24-72 hours before.</li>
    <li><strong>Outpatient procedures:</strong> May or may not require pre-auth depending on plan.</li>
    <li><strong>Routine visits:</strong> Often no pre-auth if using network provider.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</h2>
  <p>
    We assessed direct billing networks on these criteria:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Network size:</strong> Number of providers with direct billing agreements.</li>
    <li><strong>Geographic coverage:</strong> Is direct billing available where you'll actually be?</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital quality:</strong> Are the network hospitals places you'd want to be treated?</li>
    <li><strong>Provider finder tools:</strong> How easy is it to find network providers?</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-auth speed:</strong> How quickly can you get authorization for planned treatment?</li>
    <li><strong>User experience:</strong> How smooth is the actual direct billing process?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna's network size is the largest in international health insurance—over 1.5 million providers globally. This means direct billing is available in more places than any competitor.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Cigna Envoy app is excellent for finding network providers. Search by location, specialty, and direct billing availability. The app shows which facilities offer cashless service and which require reimbursement.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pre-authorization is typically processed within 24-48 hours for planned procedures. Emergency care doesn't require pre-auth—get treated first, handle paperwork after.
  </p>

  <p>
    Major hospital networks worldwide are included: Bumrungrad (Bangkok), Apollo (India), Mediclinic (Middle East/Africa), HCA (UK), and countless others. In major expat destinations, you'll find direct billing options.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Network size:</strong> 1.5M+ providers globally.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>App quality:</strong> Excellent—best in market.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>Pre-auth:</strong> 24-48 hours typical.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best overall for expats wanting extensive direct billing access.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    BUPA focuses on quality over quantity. Their 2,000+ hospital network includes top-tier facilities worldwide—places you'd actually want to be treated for serious conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network includes major international hospital groups and specialist centers. For complex care—cancer treatment, cardiac surgery, complex diagnostics—BUPA's network provides access to excellent facilities.
  </p>

  <p>
    Direct billing works smoothly. Call BUPA before scheduled treatment; they coordinate with the hospital. For emergencies, present your card and the hospital contacts BUPA directly.
  </p>

  <p>
    The app finds network providers and shows direct billing availability. Pre-authorization typically takes 24-72 hours depending on complexity.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Network size:</strong> 2,000+ quality hospitals.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>App quality:</strong> Good.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>Pre-auth:</strong> 24-72 hours.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for access to premium hospitals with direct billing.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz's direct billing strength is in Europe. If you're based in Germany, France, UK, Spain, or elsewhere in Europe, their network density provides excellent access.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network includes major European hospital groups and private clinics. Direct billing is well-established throughout Western Europe; Eastern Europe coverage is growing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Outside Europe, coverage is solid but less dense than Cigna. Major hospitals in UAE, Singapore, and other expat hubs are included, but you may need to check specific locations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Network size:</strong> Strong in Europe; good globally.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>App quality:</strong> Good.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>Pre-auth:</strong> 24-48 hours.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for Europe-based expats prioritizing regional network strength.
  </p>

  <h3>Aetna International</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna brings US healthcare network expertise to international coverage. Strong direct billing in the US and major international cities.
  </p>

  <p>
    For American expats who may need US care, Aetna's domestic network integration is valuable. Direct billing works in the US without the complexity some international insurers face.
  </p>

  <p>
    International network is solid in major expat destinations—Dubai, Singapore, London, Hong Kong. Less dense than Cigna globally, but covers key locations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Network size:</strong> Strong US; good international.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>App quality:</strong> Good.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>Pre-auth:</strong> 24-48 hours.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for US expats wanting strong domestic and international direct billing.
  </p>

  <h3>Now Health</h3>
  <p>
    Now Health's direct billing strength is in Asia—Hong Kong, Singapore, Thailand, Malaysia. For Asia-based expats, their regional network provides good direct billing access.
  </p>

  <p>
    Network is growing globally but not yet matching Cigna/BUPA scale. In Asia, though, direct billing options are competitive.
  </p>

  <p>
    The app is functional for finding providers. Pre-authorization processes work similarly to competitors.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Network size:</strong> Strong Asia; growing globally.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>App quality:</strong> Decent.</p>
  <p>
    <strong>Pre-auth:</strong> 24-48 hours.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best value for Asia-based expats wanting direct billing.
  </p>

