  <h2 id="choosing-the-right-plan">Choosing the Right Plan</h2>

  <h3>By Location</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Global coverage needed:</strong> Cigna Global (largest network)</li>
    <li><strong>Europe-based:</strong> Allianz Care (European strength)</li>
    <li><strong>Asia-based:</strong> Cigna or Now Health</li>
    <li><strong>Middle East:</strong> Cigna or BUPA</li>
    <li><strong>US-connected:</strong> Aetna International</li>
    <li><strong>Multiple regions:</strong> Cigna (most comprehensive)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>By Priority</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Maximum network size:</strong> Cigna Global</li>
    <li><strong>Premium hospital access:</strong> BUPA Global</li>
    <li><strong>Best app/digital experience:</strong> Cigna Global</li>
    <li><strong>European focus:</strong> Allianz Care</li>
    <li><strong>Value with Asia focus:</strong> Now Health</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Verifying Coverage</h3>
  <p>Before choosing, verify direct billing in your specific location:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use insurer's provider finder to check your city</li>
    <li>Call hospitals you'd likely use and ask about that insurer</li>
    <li>Ask the insurer for a network list for your destination</li>
    <li>Check reviews from expats in your area</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if the hospital I want isn't in network?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        You can still be treated—just expect to pay upfront and claim reimbursement. Out-of-network care is usually covered (check policy for any limitations), but you handle the billing rather than the insurer. Sometimes insurers can add hospitals to their network—ask if you'll use a specific facility regularly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I get pre-authorization?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Through your insurer's app, website, or by calling. Provide details of planned treatment, hospital, and doctor. They confirm coverage and send a guarantee of payment to the hospital. Allow 24-72 hours for non-emergency procedures. Emergency treatment doesn't require pre-auth.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about outpatient visits—do those have direct billing?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Depends on the provider. Large hospitals and clinic groups often have direct billing for outpatient care. Small private practices usually require pay-and-claim. The insurer's app typically shows which providers offer direct billing for which services.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I still have to pay anything with direct billing?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        You pay your deductible (if applicable) and any copays/coinsurance your plan requires. If treatment exceeds coverage limits, you pay the excess. Non-covered items (cosmetic procedures, excluded treatments) aren't direct-billed. But the main hospital bill is handled between insurer and hospital.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens in an emergency?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Go to the nearest appropriate facility—network or not. Present your insurance card; the hospital contacts your insurer. Emergency treatment doesn't require pre-authorization. If the hospital isn't in network, the insurer typically still coordinates billing for genuine emergencies.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Are pharmacies included in direct billing?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Rarely. Most pharmacy purchases are pay-and-claim. Some insurers have pharmacy networks in certain countries, but it's not universal. For expensive medications, ask your insurer about options—they may be able to arrange direct supply for very costly drugs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

